Claims CLAIMS What is claimed is: 1. A method for the determination of the antibiotic susceptibility of a bacterium, the method comprising: preparing a bacteria immobilization gel; cultivating the bacteria in a medium having a nutrient source; adding a preselected antibiotic to the medium to form a sample; incubating the antibiotic and bacteria within the medium for a preselected period of time; centrifuging the sample; washing the sample; depositing the sample on the bacteria immobilization gel ; collecting an image of the sample on the bacteria immobilization gel, through coherent Raman microscopy. 2. A method as in claim 1, wherein the sample image is collected though hyperspectral coherent Raman microscopy. 3. A method as in claim 1, wherein the sample image is collected through single frequency coherent Raman microscopy. 4. The method of claim 1, wherein the immobilization gel is comprised of an agarose gel. 5. The method of claim 1, wherein the nutrient source has a carbon source is solely composed from between 0.1-10% glucose-d7. 6. The method of claim 1, wherein the nutrient source is composed from a medium having 0-100% deuterium dioxide. 7. The method of claim 1, wherein the carbon source is composed of a combination of both glucose-d7 and deuterium dioxide. 8. The method of claim 1, wherein the Raman imaging can be stimulated Raman scattering imaging, coherent anti-Stokes Raman scattering imaging, or coherent Raman induced Kerr effect imaging. 9. A hyperspectral stimulated Raman scattering imaging apparatus for collecting images for antibiotic susceptibility testing, the apparatus comprising: a dual output femtosecond pulse laser with a repetition rate at 80 MHz, the dual out femtosecond pulse layer including: a pump beam; a Stokes beam; the Stoke beam path modulated by an acousto-optical modulator; the pump beam path having a translational stage to tune a delay between the pump beam and the Stokes beam; a combiner, the combiner adapted to combine the pump beam and the Stokes beam; a laser scanning microscope, the laser scanning microscope having an objective adapted to focus the pump beam and the Stokes beam on a sample, and an oil condenser, the oil condenser adapted to collect the laser from the sample; a filter, the filter positioned after the condenser and adapted to filter out the Stokes beam; 

 a photodiode, the photodiode positioned after the filter, the photodiode detecting the pump beam; and a lock in amplifier, the lock in amplifier adapted to extract the pump beam signal loss. 10. The imaging apparatus as in claim 9, further comprising a chirping device, the chirping device adapted to form a different pulse duration between the Stoke beam and the pump beam. 11. The imaging apparatus as in claim 10, wherein the chirping device is two 15 cm long SF57 glass rods. 12. The imaging apparatus as in claim 9, wherein a pair of filters are used. 13. The imaging apparatus as in claim 9, wherein the laser scanning microscope objective a 60x water objective. 14. The imaging apparatus of claim 9, wherein the pulse duration of the pump beam is between 1.5 and 2 ps and the pulse duration for the Stokes beam is between 1.0 and 1.4 ps. 15. The imaging apparatus of claim 9 wherein the chirping devices is adapted to form a pulse duration of 1.9 ps for the pump beam and 1.3 ps for the Stokes beam. 16. The imaging apparatus of claim 9 wherein the pump beam is a 120-fs tunable laser an having a pump beam path and the Stokes beam is a 220 fs laser centered at 1040nm having Stokes beam path. 17. A method for rapid determination of antibiotic susceptibility in bacteria using microscopy, comprising: cultivating the bacteria in a medium having a nutrient source; adding a preselected antibiotic having a pre-selected concentration to the medium to form a sample; 

 incubating the sample within the medium for a preselected period of time; centrifuging the sample; washing the sample; depositing the sample on a bacteria immobilization gel; imaging the sample on the bacteria immobilization gel, using coherent Raman microscopy. 18. The method of claim 17, wherein the coherent Raman microscopy comprises stimulated Raman scattering system. 19. The method of claim 18, wherein the stimulate Raman scattering system uses a pump beam and a Stokes beam, wherein both beams are chirped with one or more glass rods, thereby creating a pulse duration of between l-2ps for both the pump beam and Stokes beam. 20. The method of claim 19, wherein the microscopy system further comprises a translational stage to tune a delay between the pump beam and the Stokes beam.
